# Single-line simple expressions, guards, strings, and text JSX

## General

When a statement or JSX tag is simple enough to read on one line, keep it on one line. Do not introduce manual line breaks just because a formatter permits wrapping.

Prefer single-line formatting for short `const` / `let` / `var` initializers, `useRef` / `useState` hooks (with short trailing comments), ternaries with short branches, function signatures, JSX with props that fit on one line, **JSX elements whose only child is one simple `{expression}`**, short conditional children (including `t(…)`), mapped callbacks, and short callback/handler types.

## Function and method signatures

Keep **`function` / method / arrow** declarations on **one line** when the full signature (parameters, type parameters, and return type) is still easy to read.

- **Named props type**: `export function RecipeListRowLink({ recipeId, title, thumbSrc }: RecipeListRowLinkProps) {` — one line, not one parameter per line.
- **Inline object type** on destructured props: put the type object on the **same line** as the closing `}` of the destructure, with properties separated by **`;`**, e.g. `function Card({ title, children }: { title: string; children: ReactNode }) {` — do **not** break after `{` in the destructure and put each field of the inline type on its own line unless the line would be unreasonably long.
- If the signature is too long for one line, break at a meaningful boundary (e.g. after `)`) or use a **named** `*Props` type, not a four-line destructure for three short fields.

## Guards (early return / `continue` / one side-effect call)

When an `if` exists only to return or jump — that includes **`return`**, **`return null`**, **`continue`**, and side-effect calls like **`console.error` when the whole branch is a single call** — put `if`, the full condition, and that one statement on **one line**. Do **not** use `{ }` around a block whose only body is a single `return` / `continue` / one call.

**Compound conditions** (multiple `||` / `&&` / `typeof` checks) are still a single simple guard: prefer **one** physical line, e.g. `if (a || b) return null;` and `if (!tool || !ok(tool.type)) continue;`. If a line is genuinely too long, break **after** the condition and keep a single unbraced `return` / `continue` on the next line, not a `{` block for one statement.

Immediately after a single-line guard, insert one blank line before the next top-level statement in the same block (e.g. `const` or the next `if`), so guards do not run into following logic. Do not stack multiple blank lines.

## String literals

**`const` / `let` / `var` with a single string value** (prompts, copy, labels, URLs, env messages): keep the **whole initializer on one line** — assignment, opening quote, full text, and closing quote. Do not break after `=` and continue the string on the next line for “readability,” unless the string is an intentional multi-line **template literal** (embedded newlines, heredoc-style blocks). If a line is very long, prefer one logical string; if the formatter wraps, avoid *manual* splits that break the string across lines.

## Static text-only JSX

**JSX whose only child is static text** (no nested elements, no `{expr}`): keep **opening tag, text, and closing tag on one line**, e.g. `<button type="button">Save</button>`, `<span className="…">Label</span>`.

## JSX with a single simple expression child

When the **only** child is a **single** simple expression (one `{…}`) — e.g. a variable, prop, or short call like `{children}`, `{square}`, `{recipeBlock}` — and the **start tag** (with `className` / other props) still fits on one line, keep the **entire element on one line**: `<div className="…">{recipeBlock}</div>`. Do **not** break so the only child sits alone on the next line unless the line would be unreasonably long or the child is already a multi-line subtree.

**Multiple** children, **fragments** with more than one node, or **nested** block-level markup inside still use normal multi-line formatting.

## Prefer

```typescript
const ASSISTANT_CHAT_SYSTEM_PROMPT = "You are a helpful assistant for the Ratatouille recipe app. …";
if (!Number.isFinite(userId)) return new Response("Unauthorized", { status: 401 });

const modelMessages = await convertToModelMessages(messages, { tools });
if (!Array.isArray(messages)) return new Response("Expected messages array", { status: 400 });

if (typeof candidate.toolCallId !== "string" || typeof candidate.state !== "string") return null;

function Card({ title, children }: { title: string; children: ReactNode }) {
  return null;
}

const commitFromKeyboardReference = useRef(false); /* Avoids firing `onCommit` twice when Enter triggers both keydown and blur */
const [formCommitted, setFormCommitted] = useState(() => isFormMode ? props.defaultValue ?? "" : "");
const hiddenFormValue = isFormMode ? (showInput ? draft : formCommitted) : null;
const pantryOptions = useMemo(() => catalog.map((entry) => ({ value: String(entry.id), label: entry.name })), [catalog]);
const [lines, setLines] = useState<InternalLine[]>(() => withIds(initialLines));
```

