## Exceptions

- Complex expressions, long object literals, long JSX prop lists, and multi-line JSX children (nested elements) can use normal multi-line formatting.
- **Template literals** that intentionally span lines (e.g. embedded newlines) are not required to be a single source line.
- **Several children, non-trivial expression trees, or a child that is already multi-line** — use normal formatting. A **single** simple `{ident}` or similar child still prefers one line when the start tag fits (see **JSX with a single simple expression child**).
- Do not fight automated formatting for generated files. For hand-edited code, prefer a concise one-line form when it stays readable.
- If a line is genuinely too long to review comfortably, split at a meaningful boundary instead of splitting a trivial expression into many lines.

## Scope

Applies to **new and edited** code in matched files. When editing existing code, avoid churn outside the touched expressions.
